### 1865 murder in Washington, D.C., US

This is about the assassination of [Abraham Lincoln](/Abraham_Lincoln), the 16th [president of the United States](/President_of_the_United_States). It happened on April 14, 1865, at [Ford's Theatre](/Ford%27s_Theatre) in [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_D.C.). Lincoln was only a month into his second term, and the [American Civil War](/American_Civil_War) was just about done. He was watching a play, [Our American Cousin](/Our_American_Cousin), with his wife, [Mary Todd](/Mary_Todd_Lincoln). Major [Henry Rathbone](/Henry_Rathbone) and his fiancée, [Clara Harris](/Clara_Harris), were also there. Then, [John Wilkes Booth](/John_Wilkes_Booth), an actor with a penchant for the losing side – the [Confederate States](/Confederate_States) – decided to make his mark. He shot Lincoln in the head. They rushed Lincoln across the street to the [Petersen House](/Petersen_House), where he died the next morning. A rather dramatic exit, wouldn't you say?

Booth, along with his band of merry, misguided conspirators – [Lewis Powell](/Lewis_Powell_(conspirator)), [David Herold](/David_Herold), and [George Atzerodt](/George_Atzerodt) – had a change of plans. Initially, they were thinking of kidnapping Lincoln. Why? To give the Confederacy a leg up, I suppose. When that little scheme fizzled, they escalated to murder. The targets? Lincoln, [Secretary of State](/United_States_Secretary_of_State) [William H. Seward](/William_H._Seward), and [Vice President](/Vice_President_of_the_United_States) [Andrew Johnson](/Andrew_Johnson). The idea was to decapitate the [federal government](/United_States_federal_government) and somehow, miraculously, revive the dying Confederate cause. Booth managed to kill Lincoln, but Powell only managed to wound Seward. Atzerodt, bless his heart, got drunk and didn't even bother with Johnson. Pathetic.

Booth, naturally, fled. He made his way into Maryland, presumably to meet up with Herold. Meanwhile, [Secretary of War](/United_States_Secretary_of_War), [Edwin Stanton](/Edwin_Stanton), kicked off what was, at the time, the biggest manhunt in American history. Thousands of soldiers. After twelve agonizing days, they cornered Booth and Herold at a tobacco farm in [King George County, Virginia](/King_George_County,_Virginia). Booth, refusing to surrender, was shot by Sergeant [Boston Corbett](/Boston_Corbett). The rest of the crew – Powell, Herold, Atzerodt, and [Mary Surratt](/Mary_Surratt) – were rounded up and eventually hanged. John Surratt, however, proved more elusive, finally being nabbed in [Egypt](/History_of_Egypt_under_the_Muhammad_Ali_dynasty) in 1866. He got off with a mistrial. Typical.

Johnson, thrust into the presidency, was [hastily sworn in](/Inauguration_of_Andrew_Johnson) on April 15th. Lincoln's [state funeral](/State_funeral_of_Abraham_Lincoln) was a grand affair on April 19th, followed by a [funeral train](/Funeral_train) that snaked its way through seven states to Illinois. Lincoln became the third [US president to die in office](/List_of_presidents_of_the_United_States_who_died_in_office), and the first to be assassinated. The whole sordid affair sent shockwaves around the world, solidifying Lincoln's status as a [martyr](/Martyr) and ushering in the somber [Reconstruction era](/Reconstruction_era).

