### Reactions

Lincoln was mourned across the nation, North and South, &#91;92&#93; &#58;&#8202;350&#8202; and indeed, the world. &#91;96&#93; Foreign governments issued proclamations and observed periods of mourning. &#91;97&#93; &#91;98&#93; On [Easter Sunday](/Easter_Sunday), the day after his death, Lincoln was eulogized in countless sermons. &#91;92&#93; &#58;&#8202;357&#8202;

On April 18, a mile-long line of mourners, seven deep, waited to view Lincoln's body in its walnut casket in the White House's black-draped [East Room](/East_Room). Special trains brought thousands from other cities; some even slept on the [Capitol](/United_States_Capitol)'s lawn. &#91;99&#93; &#58;&#8202;120–23&#8202; Millions witnessed the funeral procession on April 19, &#91;8&#93; &#58;&#8202;213&#8202; and even more lined the 1,700-mile route of the funeral train that carried Lincoln's remains to [Springfield, Illinois](/Springfield,_Illinois). &#91;100&#93; &#58;&#8202;31–58&#8202; &#91;49&#93; &#58;&#8202;231–38&#8202;

Poet [Walt Whitman](/Walt_Whitman) penned "[When Lilacs Last in the Dooryard Bloom'd](/When_Lilacs_Last_in_the_Dooryard_Bloom%27d)" and "[O Captain! My Captain!](/O_Captain!_My_Captain!)" among other works, in tribute. &#91;101&#93; &#91;102&#93;

Ulysses S. Grant declared Lincoln "incontestably the greatest man I ever knew." &#91;9&#93; &#58;&#8202;747&#8202; Robert E. Lee expressed his sadness. &#91;103&#93; Elizabeth Blair, a Southerner by birth, noted, "Those of Southern born sympathies know now they have lost a friend willing and more powerful to protect and serve them than they can now ever hope to find again." &#91;9&#93; &#58;&#8202;744&#8202; The great orator [Frederick Douglass](/Frederick_Douglass) called the assassination an "unspeakable calamity." &#91;103&#93;

Across the Atlantic, British [Foreign Secretary](/Foreign_Secretary_(United_Kingdom)) [Lord Russell](/John_Russell,_1st_Earl_Russell) deemed Lincoln's death a "sad calamity." &#91;98&#93; In [China](/Qing_dynasty), the chief secretary of state for foreign affairs, [Prince Gong](/Prince_Gong), was "inexpressibly shocked and startled." &#91;97&#93; [Ecuadorian](/Ecuador) president [Gabriel García Moreno](/Gabriel_Garc%C3%ADa_Moreno) lamented, "Never should I have thought that the noble country of Washington would be humiliated by such a black and horrible crime; nor should I ever have thought that Mr. Lincoln would come to such a horrible end, after having served his country with such wisdom and glory under such critical circumstances." &#91;97&#93; &#91;98&#93; Liberia issued a proclamation calling Lincoln "not only the ruler of his own people, but a father to millions of a race stricken and oppressed." Haiti condemned the act as a "horrid crime." &#91;98&#93;

T. D. Bancroft, a temperance advocate, was present at the assassination and later lectured widely on the event. &#91;104&#93;

